{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"96c4ce7a-5249-40e4-839b-8389c5b6c7e3","content":"There's no pipeline file in the working directory, so here's the general guidance:\n\n## Migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform\n\n### 1. Update your test project\n\nAdd/update these NuGet packages in each test `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"MSTest\" Version=\"3.8+\" />\n<!-- TRX report output -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.6+\" />\n<!-- Code coverage -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" Version=\"17.13+\" />\n```\n\nEnable the new platform in `<PropertyGroup>`:\n\n```xml\n<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n```\n\n### 2. Replace VSTest@3 in your pipeline\n\n**Before:**\n```yaml\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblyVer2: '**/*Tests.dll'\n    resultsFolder: $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n    codeCoverageEnabled: true\n```\n\n**After:**\n```yaml\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: Run tests\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --configuration Release\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --\n      --report-trx\n      --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura\n\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: Publish TRX results\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: Publish code coverage\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/coverage.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`--report-trx`** replaces the TRX output VSTest@3 generated automatically.\n- **`--coverage`** uses the built-in `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` collector (no need for a separate `.runsettings` file).\n- Use `condition: always()` on publish tasks so results are uploaded even if tests fail.\n- The test projects now compile to **executables** (`OutputType=Exe`), so you run them via `dotnet test` on the `.csproj`, not by pointing at DLLs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"08400240-0fbd-4c71-9597-10647c441a5e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory appears to be empty. This is a general knowledge question about migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in Azure DevOps pipelines. Let me provide a helpful answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":688,"requestId":"67E3:20EF54:2A404D7:2E8AFB3:69FD345F"},"id":"6f021fcd-04a8-4683-b549-712eab8b2dc3","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:55:08.194Z","parentId":"697c9d15-c288-4fe1-8562-df5ea72dd914"}
